the ways blindness might be reconceptualized and “befriended.” Uninhibited by the trappings of traditional academic inquiry, Michalko and Goodley are unleashed, free to wander, to wonder, and to provoke within the bonds of trust and respect. Funny and thoughtful, the result is a refreshing exploration and re-evaluation of learned cultural misunderstandings of disability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlind. 0aBlindness. 0aDisability studies. 0aGuide dogs. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 0aPeople with visual disabilities. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh  ablindness.  adisability studies.  adisability.  aguide dogs.  aletters.1 aGoodley, Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177284035340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781772840353423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781772840353/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles